"Genova, Liguria, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Della","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carlo, Carmine, Geno, Amelio, Aniello, Concetta, Cosmo, Flavio, Gaetano, Gennaro, Mafalda, Raffaele.","Italian: habitational name from any of numerous minor places called Cella or Celle (from <i>cella</i> ‘cell’), because they were once the locations of hermits’ cells."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Volta","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (northern):","habitational name from any of numerous places called with the word <i>volta</i> ‘turn’, ‘vault’.","from a shortened form of a medieval personal name such as <i>Bonavolta</i>, literally ‘good fortune’, or <i>Malavolta</i> ‘bad fortune’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sibilla","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]},{"name":"Sibella","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sibilla Della Volta was born about 1145, in Italy, her father, Igno Di Guglielmo Della Volta, was 27 and her mother, Giulia Della Volta, was 26. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Oberto Spinola. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"aproximadamente 1145–":"umbes 1145–Surnud","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","1145–1226":"1145–1226","1162–1203":"1162–1203","1165–1225":"1165–1225","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1167–1252":"1167–1252","1120–1170":"1120–1170","1120–1172":"1120–1172","aproximadamente 1165":"umbes 1165","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1252":"1252","1162":"1162","1172":"1172","aproximadamente 1145":"umbes 1145","1170":"1170","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","about 1167":"umbes 1167","Itália":"Itaalia","Genova, Liguria, Italia":"Genova, Liguria, Itaalia"},"fi":{"aproximadamente 1145–":"noin 1145–Kuollut","1145–Female":"1145–Kuollut","1145–1226":"1145–1226","1162–1203":"1162–1203","1165–1225":"1165–1225","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","1167–1252":"1167–1252","1120–1170":"1120–1170","1120–1172":"1120–1172","aproximadamente 1165":"noin 1165","1165":"1165","1120":"1120","1252":"1252","1162":"1162","1172":"1172","aproximadamente 1145":"noin 1145","1170":"1170","1226":"1226","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1167":"